ce:section.ce:para:
The possible sonophotocatalytic degradation pathway of bisphenol A (BPA) was elucidated using HRMS/QToF investigations (Fig. 10
                        ). The simultaneous application of multi-frequency ultrasound energies and visible light markedly enhanced the catalytic efficiency for BPA degradation, as detailed in earlier sections. Notably, BPA was degraded through multiple pathways and overall, 16 main intermediates were identified during the sonophotocatalytic process (Table S2), primarily involving the oxidative addition of OH• radicals, ring rupture, decarboxylation, dehydroxylation, bis-benzene ring cleavage, and subsequent ring-opening reactions. During the intermediate analysis, the parent BPA ((CH3)2C(C6H4OH)2)appeared at m/z = 228. The HRMS/QToF spectra of BPA samples collected at different time intervals revealed various mass fragments attributed to the sequential radical attack on BPA and its intermediates, ultimately leading to their mineralization as shown in Fig. S9. The m/z peak corresponding to BPA was completely diminished at the 5-hours of irradiation confirming the complete mineralization of BPA. The sonophotocatalytic degradation of BPA initiated via four main decomposition pathways (Fig. 10) through the oxidative reaction of sonophotogenerated OH• radicals [87,88]. P1 (m/z = 244) and P7 (m/z = 260) were produced through hydroxylation of OH• in the bisphenol aromatic ring. Further, the oxidation products demonstrated that BPA mineralization (Pathway I) proceeded with aromatic ring cleavage and oxidation of cleaved carbons to corresponding carboxylic acids (P3/P4) which is due to the subsequent production of •O2
                        − and 1O2 species. The bisphenol ring was ruptured by the continuous oxidation of methyl carbons to carboxylic acids (P5), followed by decarboxylation reactions forming the pyrogallol derivative (P6) [89]. In Pathway II, dihydroxylated BPA was formed by the reactive OH• radical (P7) [90] subsequently bis-benzene ring cleavage was occurred tends to the formation of catechol derivatives P9a,b (m/z = 150 and 124). In Pathway III, BPA underwent dehydroxylation reactions to form P10 (m/z = 212), followed by decarboxylation reactions yielding the benzophenone product P13 (m/z = 182). In Pathway IV, the hydroxyl substitution of methyl groups in BPA yielded product P14 (m/z = 260), while P15 and P16 were formed by the further oxidation of alcohols to carboxylic acids (m/z = 274 and 288). P16 was fragmented by ring cleavage reactions, producing phenolic derivatives such as 4-hydroxyacetophenone and phenylacetic acid moiety (m/z = 136 and 152) [90,91]. Finally, the fragmented products (P6, P9a,b, P13, and P17a,b) underwent successive oxidation reactions to generate small molecular ring-opening products (m/z = 88, 90, 114, and 116) [92,93], indicating that the resulting bis-benzene molecular structure was gradually degraded, eventually producing a series of small, mineralized molecules such as H2O, CO2 and mineral acids from BPA during the triple frequency assisted sonophotocatalysis.
